<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1933-06-10T06:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1933-06-10T06:00:00-05:00" n="785" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d785">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">393.1111 M Nielsen, Niels/28:
                            Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan (<persName type="from">Grew</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-06-10T20:00:00+09:00">June 10, 1933—8
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received June 10—9:10 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>115. Department’s 56, June 9, 6 p.m. The Department’s instructions were
                            carried out this afternoon. The Foreign Office states that the Japanese
                            Army authorities in Manchuria are already doing their best to effect the
                            release of Nielsen but that the desire of the United States Government
                            as expressed by the Department will be conveyed to them immediately. The
                            Foreign Office assured the Embassy that everything possible would be
                            done.</p>
                        <p>Repeated to Peiping.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>